# Deposit & Withdrawal System (Paybill + Admin Approval)

Portable reference for the full deposit/withdrawal flow built in this project: the
Paybill deposit UI, the "Confirm to Withdraw" → "Pending Request" withdrawal UI, the
shared transaction ledger, the admin approve/reject panels, the realtime socket
wiring, and the local-cache resilience layer that keeps it all in sync. Written so
you can lift the pattern into a different codebase.

Stack this was built on: **Express + a generic key-value store** (Postgres in
production, JSON files in dev — see "Storage" below) on the server, **React +
Socket.IO client** on the frontend. Nothing here is framework-specific in concept —
swap the storage layer and HTTP framework and the same model still applies.

---

## 1. The core idea

Money never moves instantly from a user action. Every deposit and every withdrawal
is a **request** that lands in a shared transaction ledger with `status: 'pending'`,
and only an admin clicking Approve/Reject turns it into money moving:

| Action     | What happens immediately                                   | What happens on admin approve         | What happens on admin reject          |
|------------|--------------------------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------|-----------------------------------------|
| Deposit    | Tx created as `pending`. Balance **untouched**.               | Balance credited, tx → `completed`.     | Tx → `rejected`. No balance change.     |
| Withdrawal | Tx created as `pending`. Balance **debited immediately** (funds reserved so they can't be double-spent while the request sits in the queue). | Nothing changes — money already left the balance. Tx → `completed`. | Balance **refunded**. Tx → `rejected`.  |

This asymmetry (deposit doesn't touch balance until approved; withdrawal touches it
immediately and refunds on reject) is the one thing to keep straight when you port
this — it's not a bug, it's the whole point: a user can't spend money they've asked
to withdraw while the request is still sitting in the queue.

---

## 2. Data model

One shared "transactions" store, keyed by user id → array of transaction records
(newest first, capped at 500 per user). A single record shape covers deposits,
withdrawals, bet stakes, cash-outs, admin balance adjustments, referral bonuses —
anything that touches a wallet gets one row here.

```js
{
  id: 'tx-<timestamp>-<random4>',   // e.g. tx-1784201165513-jo50
  userId: 'u-...',
  at: '2026-07-16T11:26:05.513Z',   // ISO timestamp
  kind: 'deposit' | 'withdraw' | 'bet_placed' | 'cash_out' | 'admin_adjust' | 'referral_bonus',
  amount: 600,                       // always positive for deposit/withdraw; the UI decides the sign/icon
  method: 'momo' | 'vodafone' | 'airteltigo' | 'card' | 'paybill',
  status: 'pending' | 'completed' | 'rejected',
  balanceAfter: 450,                 // snapshot of balance right after this tx was applied

  // populated only once the admin acts:
  approvedAt: '2026-07-16T11:29:47.951Z',
  approvedBy: 'admin@example.com',
  rejectedAt: '2026-07-16T11:26:42.166Z',
  rejectedBy: 'admin@example.com',
  rejectReason: 'Could not verify payment' | null,
}
```

`pushTx(userId, tx)` is the one helper that appends a record:

```js
function pushTx(userId, tx) {
  const id = `tx-${Date.now()}-${Math.random().toString(36).slice(2, 6)}`;
  const entry = { id, userId, at: new Date().toISOString(), ...tx };
  const list = txStore.get(userId) || [];
  txStore.set(userId, [entry, ...list].slice(0, 500));
  return entry;
}
```

### Storage

`createStore(name, fallback)` returns a small key→value API (`get`, `set`, `delete`,
`all`, `list`) backed by **Postgres when `DATABASE_URL` is set, otherwise JSON files
on disk** — same interface either way, so route code never needs to know which one
is active. If you're porting this into a project that already has its own DB layer,
just implement the same four methods against whatever you're using; nothing else
needs to change.

```js
const txStore = createStore('transactions', {});
txStore.get(userId)        // -> array of tx for this user (or undefined)
txStore.set(userId, list)  // -> replace the whole array
txStore.delete(userId)     // -> wipe this user's history entirely
txStore.all()               // -> { [userId]: [...tx] } for every user (admin queries scan this)
```

Admin list/history endpoints scan `txStore.all()` and filter by `kind`/`status` —
fine at the scale this was built for; swap for an indexed query (`WHERE kind = ...`)
if you're porting this to a real relational table with volume.

---

## 3. Server API reference

### User-facing (`/api/wallet/*`)

| Method | Path | Body | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `GET`  | `/wallet/transactions` | — | Paginated (`?offset&limit`), newest first, for the authenticated user only. |
| `GET`  | `/wallet/rules` | — | Returns `minDeposit`, `minWithdraw`, `withdrawDepositRatio`, `totalDeposited`, `maxWithdrawByRatio` — whatever numbers your UI needs to render live limits. |
| `POST` | `/wallet/deposit` | `{ amount, method }` | Creates a `pending` deposit tx. **No balance change.** Notifies the user (`wallet:pending`) and admins (`wallet:deposit`). |
| `POST` | `/wallet/withdraw` | `{ amount, method }` | Runs eligibility gates (see §6), then **debits the balance immediately**, creates a `pending` withdraw tx. Notifies the user (`wallet:update` + `withdraw:pending`) and admins (`wallet:withdraw`). |

```js
router.post('/deposit', requireAuth, validate(depositSchema), asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
  const { amount, method = 'momo' } = req.body;
  const user = req.user;

  const tx = pushTx(user.id, { kind: 'deposit', amount, method, status: 'pending' });
  logActivity(user.id, { kind: 'deposit', amount, method });
  emitToUser(user.id, 'wallet:pending', { transaction: tx, amount, method });
  emitAdmin('wallet:deposit', { userId: user.id, amount, method, transactionId: tx.id });
  res.json({ ok: true, transaction: tx });
}));

router.post('/withdraw', requireAuth, requireEmailVerified, validate(withdrawSchema), asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
  const { amount, method = 'momo' } = req.body;
  const user = req.user;

  // ...eligibility gates go here (blocked check, stage gate, min-withdraw,
  // deposit-ratio check, balance check — see §6)...

  // Reserve the funds immediately; admin approval finalizes or refunds it.
  const updated = await adjustBalance(user.id, -amount);
  const tx = pushTx(user.id, { kind: 'withdraw', amount, method, status: 'pending', balanceAfter: updated.balance });
  logActivity(user.id, { kind: 'withdraw_requested', amount, method });
  emitToUser(user.id, 'wallet:update', { balance: updated.balance, delta: -amount, reason: 'withdraw_pending', method });
  emitToUser(user.id, 'withdraw:pending', { transaction: tx, amount, method });
  emitAdmin('wallet:withdraw', { userId: user.id, amount, method, transactionId: tx.id });
  res.json({ ok: true, account: updated, transaction: tx });
}));
```

### Admin (`/api/admin/deposits/*`, `/api/admin/withdrawals/*`)

Deposits and withdrawals get **parallel, near-identical route files** — copy one to
make the other. Both are gated behind an admin role check (`finance_admin` or above
in this project; adjust to whatever your RBAC calls it).

| Method | Path | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| `GET`  | `/deposits/pending` \| `/withdrawals/pending` | Scans the whole store for `kind + status:'pending'`, attaches a `user` summary (`id, email, displayName, phone`) to each row, sorts newest-first. |
| `GET`  | `/deposits/history` \| `/withdrawals` | Same scan, no status filter (or an optional `?status=` / `?q=` search) — for the History tab. |
| `POST` | `/deposits/:id/approve` \| `/withdrawals/:id/approve` | Finds the tx by id across *all* users (it's not scoped to one user in the URL — the id alone is enough), verifies it's still `pending`, marks `completed`, stamps `approvedAt`/`approvedBy`. **Deposit approve also credits the balance** (withdrawal approve doesn't — money already left). |
| `POST` | `/deposits/:id/reject` \| `/withdrawals/:id/reject` | Same lookup, marks `rejected`, stamps `rejectedAt`/`rejectedBy`/`rejectReason`. **Withdrawal reject also refunds the balance** (deposit reject doesn't — nothing was ever credited). |
| `GET`  | `/withdrawals/stats` | Aggregate counts/totals for a stats-card row (`totalCount`, `todayTotal`, `pendingCount`, a 30-day daily-volume series, etc.) — cosmetic, skip if you don't need a chart. |

Finding a transaction by id across every user (both approve/reject routes need this,
since the admin only has the tx id, not the owner's user id):

```js
function findPendingTx(txStore, txId) {
  const all = txStore.all() || {};
  for (const [userId, txs] of Object.entries(all)) {
    for (const tx of txs) {
      if (tx.id === txId) return { tx, userId };
    }
  }
  return { tx: null, userId: null };
}
```

Deposit approve (credits balance, and — project-specific bonus logic you can drop —
auto-promotes a brand-new account past a "verification stage" the first time a big
enough deposit clears, and pays a referral bonus on a user's very first deposit):

```js
router.post('/:id/approve', requireAdmin, requireRole('finance_admin'), asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
  const { tx: foundTx, userId: foundUserId } = findPendingTx(txStore, req.params.id);
  if (!foundTx) throw notFound('Transaction not found');
  if (foundTx.kind !== 'deposit' || foundTx.status !== 'pending') {
    throw badRequest('Transaction is not a pending deposit');
  }

  const user = getUserById(foundUserId);
  const updated = await updateUser(foundUserId, {
    balance: Number((user.balance + foundTx.amount).toFixed(2)),
    totalDeposited: Number((Number(user.totalDeposited || 0) + foundTx.amount).toFixed(2)),
  });

  const userTxs = txStore.get(foundUserId) || [];
  const updatedTxs = userTxs.map((t) => t.id === req.params.id
    ? { ...t, status: 'completed', balanceAfter: updated.balance, approvedAt: new Date().toISOString(), approvedBy: req.admin.email }
    : t);
  txStore.set(foundUserId, updatedTxs);

  emitToUser(foundUserId, 'deposit:approved', { transaction: updatedTxs.find((t) => t.id === req.params.id), account: updated });
  emitAdmin('deposit:approved', { userId: foundUserId, amount: foundTx.amount, transactionId: req.params.id, approvedBy: req.admin.email });
  audit(req, { action: 'deposit.approve', target: foundUserId, targetType: 'user', meta: { amount: foundTx.amount } });
  res.json({ ok: true, transaction: updatedTxs.find((t) => t.id === req.params.id) });
}));
```

Withdrawal reject (the refund path — the one deposit reject *doesn't* need):

```js
router.post('/:id/reject', requireAdmin, requireRole('finance_admin'),
  validate(z.object({ reason: z.string().max(500).optional() })),
  asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
    const { tx: foundTx, userId: foundUserId } = findPendingTx(txStore, req.params.id);
    if (!foundTx) throw notFound('Transaction not found');
    if (foundTx.kind !== 'withdraw' || foundTx.status !== 'pending') {
      throw badRequest('Transaction is not a pending withdrawal');
    }

    const updatedUser = await adjustBalance(foundUserId, foundTx.amount, { allowNegative: true });

    const userTxs = txStore.get(foundUserId) || [];
    const updatedTxs = userTxs.map((t) => t.id === req.params.id
      ? { ...t, status: 'rejected', balanceAfter: updatedUser.balance, rejectedAt: new Date().toISOString(), rejectedBy: req.admin.email, rejectReason: req.body?.reason || null }
      : t);
    txStore.set(foundUserId, updatedTxs);

    emitToUser(foundUserId, 'wallet:update', { balance: updatedUser.balance, delta: foundTx.amount, reason: 'withdraw_rejected' });
    emitToUser(foundUserId, 'withdraw:rejected', { transaction: updatedTxs.find((t) => t.id === req.params.id), reason: req.body?.reason });
    emitAdmin('withdraw:rejected', { userId: foundUserId, amount: foundTx.amount, transactionId: req.params.id, rejectedBy: req.admin.email });
    audit(req, { action: 'withdraw.reject', target: foundUserId, targetType: 'user', meta: { amount: foundTx.amount, reason: req.body?.reason } });
    res.json({ ok: true });
  })
);
```

### Admin: delete a user's history

One more admin-only route worth carrying over — a "Delete All Transaction History"
button on a user's profile that wipes their tx array. Two things make this safe:

1. It never touches `balance` or `totalDeposited` (those are separate persisted
   fields on the user record, not derived from the tx list) — only the *log*
   disappears, not the money or the verification math that depends on lifetime
   deposit totals.
2. It stamps a `txClearedAt` timestamp on the user record (not just an ephemeral
   socket push) so a client that was offline at the moment of deletion still
   catches up — see §7.

```js
router.delete('/:id/transactions', requireAdmin, requireRole('finance_admin'), asyncHandler(async (req, res) => {
  const u = getUserById(req.params.id);
  if (!u) throw notFound('User not found');
  const count = (txStore.get(u.id) || []).length;
  txStore.delete(u.id);
  const updated = await updateUser(u.id, { txClearedAt: new Date().toISOString() });
  emitToUser(u.id, 'wallet:transactions-cleared', { at: updated.txClearedAt });
  res.json({ ok: true, cleared: count, user: updated });
}));
```

---

## 4. Realtime events (Socket.IO)

Two namespaces: a per-user room (`user:<id>`, joined on socket connect once
authenticated) for player-facing pushes, and an admin room (`global`) for the
ops panel. `emitToUser(userId, event, payload)` and `emitAdmin(event, payload)`
are the only two primitives you need:

```js
export function emitToUser(userId, event, payload) {
  if (!liveNs || !userId) return;
  liveNs.to(`user:${userId}`).emit(event, payload);
}
export function emitAdmin(event, payload) {
  if (!adminNs) return;
  adminNs.to('global').emit(event, payload);
}
```

| Event | Direction | Payload | Fired when |
|---|---|---|---|
| `wallet:pending` | → user | `{ transaction, amount, method }` | Deposit submitted. |
| `wallet:deposit` | → admin | `{ userId, amount, method, transactionId }` | Deposit submitted (admin's "new request" toast/chime). |
| `deposit:approved` | → user | `{ transaction, account }` | Admin approved a deposit. |
| `deposit:rejected` | → user | `{ transaction, reason }` | Admin rejected a deposit. |
| `deposit:approved` / `deposit:rejected` | → admin | `{ userId, amount, transactionId, approvedBy/rejectedBy }` | Mirror of the above, for the admin's own activity feed. |
| `withdraw:pending` | → user | `{ transaction, amount, method }` | Withdrawal submitted. |
| `wallet:withdraw` | → admin | `{ userId, amount, method, transactionId }` | Withdrawal submitted. |
| `wallet:update` | → user | `{ balance, delta, reason, method }` | Any balance change: withdrawal reserved, withdrawal refunded, bet placed, cash-out, admin adjustment — generic "your balance just changed" event the client always listens for. |
| `withdraw:approved` | → user | `{ transaction }` | Admin approved a withdrawal. |
| `withdraw:rejected` | → user | `{ transaction, reason }` | Admin rejected a withdrawal (balance already refunded via `wallet:update` above). |
| `withdraw:approved` / `withdraw:rejected` | → admin | `{ userId, amount, transactionId, approvedBy/rejectedBy }` | Admin activity mirror. |
| `wallet:transactions-cleared` | → user | `{ at: <ISO timestamp> }` | Admin wiped this user's tx history. |

---

## 5. Client: the Paybill deposit flow

**UX shape:** tap Deposit → amount entry (quick-amount chips + manual input) → tap
"Top Up Now" → a **PayBill instructions card** appears (merchant paybill number,
your account reference, step-by-step USSD instructions, a live status pill) → tap
the card's own "Top Up Now" button to actually submit → the card flips its status
pill live as the admin approves/rejects, with a **flash animation** (green pulse on
approve, a small shake on reject) and reverts to "Pending" after 60s so it always
looks like a fresh, in-flight request rather than a permanent receipt.

### State (lives in the app-wide account/wallet provider, not the page)

```js
const [depositAmt, setDepositAmt]     = useState(String(MIN_DEPOSIT));
const [depositTab, setDepositTab]     = useState('paybill');   // 'paybill' | 'card'
const [showPaybillInstructions, setShowPaybillInstructions] = useState(false);
const [paybillMeta, setPaybillMeta]   = useState(() => ({
  reference: String(Math.floor(100000000 + Math.random() * 900000000)), // cosmetic ref shown before submit
  depositId: String(Math.floor(1000 + Math.random() * 9000)),
}));
// The paybill deposit actually submitted to the backend for admin review.
const [paybillTx, setPaybillTx]             = useState(null);   // { id, status, amount }
const [paybillSubmitting, setPaybillSubmitting] = useState(false);
const [paybillRefreshing, setPaybillRefreshing] = useState(false);
const [paybillJustResolved, setPaybillJustResolved] = useState(false); // triggers the flash animation once
```

Why a `paybillTxRef` mirror of `paybillTx` exists: the socket handlers below are
registered in an effect keyed on `accountId` (so the socket doesn't get torn down
and rebuilt on every balance change) — by the time an event fires, the closure's
`paybillTx` could be stale, so the handlers read `paybillTxRef.current` instead.

### Revert-to-pending timer

The card is a **live status display, not a permanent receipt** — once resolved, it
quietly reverts to "Pending" after a minute so re-opening the deposit dialog later
never shows a stale "Approved"/"Rejected" from days ago sitting there looking current:

```js
useEffect(() => {
  if (paybillTx?.status !== 'completed' && paybillTx?.status !== 'rejected') return;
  const timer = setTimeout(() => {
    setPaybillTx((prev) => (prev && prev.status !== 'pending') ? { ...prev, status: 'pending' } : prev);
    setPaybillJustResolved(false);
  }, 60_000);
  return () => clearTimeout(timer);
}, [paybillTx?.status, paybillTx?.id]);
```

### Submitting the paybill deposit

```js
const submitPaybillTopUp = async () => {
  if (paybillSubmitting || paybillTx) return;               // one submit per dialog open
  const amt = parseFloat(String(depositAmt).replace(/,/g, ''));
  if (!Number.isFinite(amt) || amt < MIN_DEPOSIT) { setErr(`Minimum deposit is GHS ${MIN_DEPOSIT}.`); return; }
  try {
    setPaybillSubmitting(true);
    const data = await apiDeposit(amt, 'paybill');            // POST /wallet/deposit
    if (data?.transaction) {
      setPaybillTx({ id: data.transaction.id, status: 'pending', amount: amt });
    }
    toast('Payment submitted — waiting for admin confirmation.', 'info');
  } catch (e) {
    setErr(e.message || 'Could not submit deposit.');
  } finally {
    setPaybillSubmitting(false);
  }
};
```

A manual "Refresh Status" fallback (in case the socket missed it — never trust
realtime as your *only* path to truth):

```js
const refreshPaybillStatus = async () => {
  if (!paybillTx || paybillRefreshing) return;
  try {
    setPaybillRefreshing(true);
    const data = await fetchTransactions();
    const match = (data?.transactions || []).find((t) => t.id === paybillTx.id);
    if (match) {
      const nextStatus = match.status === 'completed' ? 'completed' : match.status === 'rejected' ? 'rejected' : 'pending';
      if (nextStatus !== paybillTx.status && nextStatus !== 'pending') setPaybillJustResolved(true);
      setPaybillTx((prev) => prev ? { ...prev, status: nextStatus } : prev);
    }
  } finally {
    setPaybillRefreshing(false);
  }
};
```

### Live socket handlers (approve/reject → update the card + fire a modal)

```js
onLive('deposit:approved', ({ transaction, account: updatedAccount }) => {
  if (updatedAccount) setAccount(updatedAccount);
  if (paybillTxRef.current?.id === transaction?.id) {
    setPaybillTx((prev) => prev ? { ...prev, status: 'completed' } : prev);
    setPaybillJustResolved(true);                 // triggers the green flash
  }
  toast(`Deposit approved! GHS ${amt} credited.`, 'success');
  addNotification({ id: `deposit-approved-${transaction.id}`, title: 'Deposit approved', body: `GHS ${amt} has been credited to your wallet.`, kind: 'deposit_approved' });
  osNotify({ title: 'Deposit approved', body: `GHS ${amt} has been credited to your wallet.` }); // OS-level push if permitted
  setDepositResults((prev) => [...prev, { kind: 'approved', amount: transaction.amount, txId: transaction.id, at: Date.now() }]);
});

onLive('deposit:rejected', ({ transaction, reason }) => {
  if (paybillTxRef.current?.id === transaction?.id) {
    setPaybillTx((prev) => prev ? { ...prev, status: 'rejected' } : prev);
    setPaybillJustResolved(true);                 // triggers the shake
  }
  toast(`Deposit rejected${reason ? ': ' + reason : ''}.`, 'warn');
  setDepositResults((prev) => [...prev, { kind: 'rejected', amount: transaction.amount, reason, txId: transaction.id, at: Date.now() }]);
});
```

`depositResults` is a **queue, not a single value** — a burst of decisions (rare,
but possible if an admin clears a backlog) never silently overwrites an unread
popup: `DepositResultModal` always shows `depositResults[0]` and pops the head on
close.

### `DepositResultModal` — the centered "your deposit was decided" popup

Why a real `<dialog>` modal and not just a toast: toasts disappear after a few
seconds and this is money — the user must see it, and OS push notifications need
permission many people decline, so the in-app modal is the *guaranteed*-visible
path.

```jsx
export default function DepositResultModal({ result, onClose }) {
  const dlgRef = useRef(null);
  const isOpen = !!result;

  useEffect(() => {
    const dlg = dlgRef.current;
    if (!dlg) return;
    if (isOpen) { if (!dlg.open) try { dlg.showModal(); } catch {} }
    else if (dlg.open) { try { dlg.close(); } catch {} }
  }, [isOpen]);
  // NOTE: always render the same <dialog>; gate only the *inner content* on
  // `result`. Early-returning a bare <dialog> when result is null causes React
  // to reuse the DOM node in a way that drops the open/close effect on
  // back-to-back approve→reject transitions.

  const approved = result?.kind === 'approved';
  return (
    <dialog ref={dlgRef} onClose={onClose} onClick={(e) => { if (e.target === dlgRef.current) onClose?.(); }}>
      {result && (
        <div>
          <div>{approved ? '✓' : '✕'}</div>
          <h2>{approved ? 'Deposit approved' : 'Deposit rejected'}</h2>
          <p>{approved ? `GHS ${result.amount} has been credited to your wallet.` : `Your GHS ${result.amount} deposit was not approved.`}</p>
          {!approved && result.reason && <p>Reason: {result.reason}</p>}
          <button onClick={onClose}>OK</button>
        </div>
      )}
    </dialog>
  );
}
```

### Flash animation CSS (status pill / card border)

```css
.paybill-approved-flash { animation: paybill-approved-flash 1.4s ease-out; }
@keyframes paybill-approved-flash {
  0%   { box-shadow: 0 0 0 0 rgba(34, 197, 94, 0.55); }
  60%  { box-shadow: 0 0 0 10px rgba(34, 197, 94, 0); }
  100% { box-shadow: 0 0 0 0 rgba(34, 197, 94, 0); }
}
.paybill-rejected-flash { animation: paybill-rejected-flash 0.5s ease-in-out; }
@keyframes paybill-rejected-flash {
  0%, 100% { transform: translateX(0); }
  25%      { transform: translateX(-4px); }
  75%      { transform: translateX(4px); }
}
```

Applied conditionally on the card wrapper: `justResolved && status === 'Approved' ?
'paybill-approved-flash' : justResolved && status === 'Rejected' ?
'paybill-rejected-flash' : ''`.

### `PaybillInstructions` component contract

Reusable for both deposit and withdraw contexts (`context="deposit" | "withdraw"`),
so you only need one component:

```
props: {
  paybillId, merchantName, accountRef, amount, reference, depositId,
  status: 'Pending' | 'Approved' | 'Rejected',
  context: 'deposit' | 'withdraw',
  submitted, submitting, onSubmit,       // deposit-only: the "Top Up Now" -> submit step
  refreshing, onRefreshStatus,           // deposit-only: manual status refresh
  justResolved,                          // triggers the flash animation once
  onGoBack,
}
```

It renders: a details card (paybill number, merchant name, amount, reference, your
registered number, deposit id, live status pill — deposit context only), a
step-by-step USSD instruction list (network-specific for withdraw; a fixed sequence
for deposit), a footer note, and the submit/refresh/back buttons.

---

## 6. Client: the withdrawal Confirm → Pending flow

**UX shape:** fill amount → tap "Withdraw Now" → gates run client-side first (see
below) → if everything's clear, a **"Confirm to Withdraw"** modal appears (remaining
balance after this withdrawal, network, masked mobile number, amount; Cancel/Confirm)
→ tapping Confirm actually calls the API → on success, swap straight into a
**"Pending Request"** modal (spinner icon, explanation text, Transactions/Home links).
Two different background animations distinguish the two steps: a slow breathing
glow behind the confirm card (calm, "review this"), a spinning ring + pulsing dots
behind the pending card (active, "this is in flight").

### Client-side eligibility gates (before the confirm modal ever shows)

These mirror the server's gates exactly — the server is the actual enforcement,
the client copy exists purely so the user gets an explanatory popup instead of a
generic error:

```js
const handleSubmit = (e) => {
  e.preventDefault();
  if (!isAmountValid || busy) return;
  if (isBlocked)               { setShowBlocked(true); return; }        // account locked, needs admin review
  if (stage === 0 || stage === 1) { setShowDepositReq(true); return; }  // not verified yet
  if (stage === 2)             { setShowExtraDeposit(true); return; }   // needs more deposit history first
  setShowConfirmWithdraw(true);                                        // all clear -> confirm step
};
```

### Confirm → submit → pending

```js
const confirmWithdraw = async () => {
  try {
    setBusy(true);
    const data = await withdraw(amtNum, method);      // POST /wallet/withdraw
    if (data.account) setAccount(data.account);        // balance already reflects the reservation
    setShowConfirmWithdraw(false);
    setShowPendingRequest(true);
    setAmount('');
  } catch (e) {
    setShowConfirmWithdraw(false);
    setErr(e.message || 'Withdrawal failed.');
  } finally {
    setBusy(false);
  }
};
```

### Masking the mobile number for the confirm screen

```js
function maskPhone(phone) {
  const raw = String(phone || '').replace(/\D/g, '');
  if (raw.length < 5) return phone || '';
  return `${raw.slice(0, 2)}****${raw.slice(-3)}`;   // "0246350785" -> "02****785"
}
```

