## 7. Client: local cache resilience (read this before you skip it)

The wallet/transactions list is **not purely server-driven** — the client keeps a
localStorage mirror per account and merges it with whatever the server returns:

```js
// txCache.js
const keyFor = (userId) => `bv_tx_cache:${String(userId).toLowerCase()}`;

export function readTxCache(userId) { /* JSON.parse(localStorage.getItem(keyFor(userId))) || [] */ }
export function writeTxCache(userId, txs) { /* localStorage.setItem(keyFor(userId), JSON.stringify(txs.slice(0, 50))) */ }
export function appendTxCache(userId, tx) { /* de-dupe by id, prepend, writeTxCache */ }

export function mergeTxLists(serverList, cacheList) {
  const byId = new Map();
  for (const t of cacheList || []) if (t?.id) byId.set(t.id, t);
  for (const t of serverList || []) if (t?.id) byId.set(t.id, t); // server wins on id collision
  return [...byId.values()].sort((a, b) => new Date(b.at) - new Date(a.at)).slice(0, 50);
}
```

**Why this exists:** if your backend has any chance of losing state (an ephemeral
filesystem, a free-tier host that wipes disk on restart, a flaky cache layer —
whatever the equivalent risk is in your deployment), a user's recent deposit/
withdraw history shouldn't visibly vanish just because the server forgot. The
client remembers what it last saw and fills in gaps.

**The trap this creates:** the merge logic can't tell the difference between "the
server forgot this record" (bad, backfill it) and "an admin intentionally deleted
this record" (good, let it go). Left alone, an admin's "delete transaction history"
action looks like it silently failed — the deleted rows keep reappearing from the
user's own browser cache.

**The fix — two layers, because one alone isn't enough:**

1. **Live layer** (works only if the user is connected *at the exact moment* the
   admin acts): the server pushes `wallet:transactions-cleared`, the client clears
   its cache for that account immediately.

   ```js
   onLive('wallet:transactions-cleared', (payload) => {
     if (payload?.at) reconcileTxCleared(accountId, payload.at);
     else clearTxCache(accountId);
   });
   ```

2. **Persisted layer** (the one that actually matters — catches every case the live
   push misses, e.g. the browser was closed at the time): the server stamps a
   `txClearedAt` timestamp on the *user record itself*, not just an ephemeral socket
   event, and returns it on every `/auth/me` response. The client compares that
   timestamp against a per-account marker it stored last time it reacted, and
   purges the cache if it's different — meaning it self-corrects the very next time
   the app loads, online or not, socket-connected or not.

   ```js
   // txCache.js
   const clearedMarkerKey = (userId) => `bv_tx_cleared_marker:${String(userId).toLowerCase()}`;

   export function reconcileTxCleared(userId, txClearedAt) {
     const seen = localStorage.getItem(clearedMarkerKey(userId));
     if (seen === txClearedAt) return;          // already reacted to this exact clear event
     clearTxCache(userId);
     localStorage.setItem(clearedMarkerKey(userId), txClearedAt);
   }

   // called on every account refresh (e.g. app boot, tab refocus, polling tick):
   const data = await fetchMe();
   setAccount(data.account);
   if (data.account?.txClearedAt) reconcileTxCleared(data.account.id, data.account.txClearedAt);
   ```

   Server side, the delete route sets it: `updateUser(userId, { txClearedAt: new
   Date().toISOString() })`, and it needs to survive whatever "safe/public user"
   stripping function your `/auth/me` route uses — an easy thing to forget if that
   function is an explicit field whitelist rather than a spread-everything-except
   the-secrets shape.

**Rule of thumb if you port this:** any time you add a way to *intentionally* wipe
or mutate what the server holds for a user (not just normal money-in/money-out
flows), ask whether a local resilience cache exists that could resurrect the old
state, and give that mutation the same two-layer signal (live push + a persisted
field the client reconciles against on every refresh) — the live push alone always
has a hole.

---

## 8. Admin approval UI pattern (Pending / History tabs)

Both `/admin/deposits` and `/admin/withdrawals` use the identical shape — copy one
page to build the other:

- Two sub-tabs: **Pending** (default) and **History**.
- Pending tab: polls every 8s (`setTimeout` chain, not `setInterval`, so a slow
  request can't overlap the next tick), shows a stat row (pending count / total
  amount / oldest-pending age), a table with Approve/Reject icon buttons per row.
- History tab: lazily fetched only when the tab is opened, shows a stat row
  (total / approved count / rejected count) and a status-badged table.
- **Live notification on new pending item:** the admin socket event
  (`wallet:deposit` / `wallet:withdraw`) triggers a toast, an OS notification (if
  permitted), a short WebAudio chime, and an immediate re-fetch — so the admin
  doesn't have to wait for the 8s poll. A `seenIdsRef` Set de-dupes so a reload +
  socket replay never double-fires the chime for the same transaction.

```js
function playChime() {
  const ctx = new (window.AudioContext || window.webkitAudioContext)();
  const o = ctx.createOscillator(), g = ctx.createGain();
  o.connect(g); g.connect(ctx.destination);
  o.type = 'sine';
  o.frequency.setValueAtTime(660, ctx.currentTime);
  o.frequency.exponentialRampToValueAtTime(990, ctx.currentTime + 0.18);
  g.gain.setValueAtTime(0.0001, ctx.currentTime);
  g.gain.exponentialRampToValueAtTime(0.15, ctx.currentTime + 0.02);
  g.gain.exponentialRampToValueAtTime(0.0001, ctx.currentTime + 0.4);
  o.start(); o.stop(ctx.currentTime + 0.42);
  setTimeout(() => ctx.close(), 600);
}

useEffect(() => {
  const off = onAdmin('wallet:deposit', (payload) => {   // swap for 'wallet:withdraw' on the withdrawals page
    if (seenIdsRef.current.has(payload.transactionId)) return;
    seenIdsRef.current.add(payload.transactionId);
    show(`New deposit request — GHS ${payload.amount}`, 'info');
    osNotify({ title: 'New deposit request', body: `GHS ${payload.amount} from user ${payload.userId}` });
    playChime();
    load();     // pull the row in immediately instead of waiting for the poll
  });
  return () => off?.();
}, [load, show]);
```

Reject action, single-click with a native `confirm()` guard (drop the `confirm()`
if you want a tighter one-click flow — it's a UX choice, not a safety requirement,
since reject is always reversible from the user's side by re-submitting):

```js
const handleReject = async (id) => {
  if (!window.confirm('Reject this withdrawal? The reserved funds will be refunded to the user.')) return;
  setBusyId(id);
  try {
    await adminRejectWithdrawal(id, {});
    show('Withdrawal rejected — funds refunded', 'success');
    load();
  } finally {
    setBusyId(null);
  }
};
```

---

## 9. Business rules this project layered on top (swap or delete per project)

These are specific to the betting-platform this was built for — keep the mechanism
(§1–§8), replace the numbers/rules with whatever your product needs:

- **Minimum deposit / minimum withdrawal** — flat floors (`MIN_DEPOSIT`,
  `MIN_WITHDRAW`), enforced by a `zod` schema on the request body.
- **Withdrawal eligibility gates**, checked in this order, each with its own
  explanatory popup on the client so a rejected withdrawal always tells the user
  *why*, not just "failed":
  1. Account blocked → show a "blocked" modal instructing them to deposit X and
     contact support.
  2. Verification "stage" too low → show a "you need to deposit and get verified"
     modal (stage promotion is otherwise 100% manual, admin-driven — the one
     automatic exception being a first-deposit-over-threshold auto-promotion from
     "brand new" to the first stage).
  3. Stage-scaled minimum withdrawal (higher stages unlock bigger single-withdrawal
     amounts) → show "additional deposit required" with the exact shortfall.
  4. **Deposit-to-withdrawal ratio** — you must have *lifetime approved deposits*
     ≥ some percentage of the amount you're trying to withdraw (a basic anti-abuse
     rule: you can't withdraw far more than you've ever put in).
  5. Balance check (obviously).
- **Referral bonus** on a user's very first approved deposit, paid to whoever
  referred them.
- **Per-account overrides** — the pattern for a special account that should ignore
  one specific rule (e.g. a demo/test account exempt from the stage-scaled minimum
  withdrawal) without touching any of the other gates: check an `isSpecialAccount(user)`
  predicate and only override the *one* number that needs to differ, leaving every
  other check (balance, ratio, stage eligibility, blocked status) exactly as-is for
  that account too. Don't build a full bypass "if special account, skip everything"
  branch — that's how a demo account quietly becomes a real security hole.

None of §9 is required for the core pattern in §1–§8 to work — it's just the
specific gating logic this project needed layered on top of a generic "pending →
admin decides" ledger.

---

## 10. Porting checklist

- [ ] One transaction store, one shape, shared by deposits/withdrawals/bets/anything
      else that touches a balance (§2).
- [ ] Deposit route: create `pending` tx, **no balance change** (§3).
- [ ] Withdraw route: run your eligibility gates, **debit balance immediately**,
      create `pending` tx (§3, §9).
- [ ] Admin approve/reject routes for both, mirrored (§3) — remember deposit-approve
      credits, withdraw-reject refunds; the other two directions are no-ops on balance.
- [ ] Socket events for both directions, user-room + admin-room (§4).
- [ ] Deposit UI: instructions card → submit → live status pill → flash animation →
      centered result modal, with a manual refresh fallback (§5).
- [ ] Withdraw UI: client-side gate popups → Confirm modal → Pending modal, distinct
      background animations for each (§6).
- [ ] Admin UI: Pending/History tabs, live chime + toast on new items, single-click
      approve/reject (§8).
- [ ] If your backend storage can ever lose state: a local resilience cache — and
      if you also build an admin "wipe this user's data" action, give it the
      **persisted marker**, not just a live push, or the delete will look broken
      to anyone offline at the moment it ran (§7 — don't skip this one).
